WEBVTT

00:01.649 --> 00:04.088
Two one six four two zero

00:04.121 --> 00:06.059
one nine eight nine.

00:06.061 --> 00:09.836
And that, little lady,
is pi to a thousand places.

00:09.838 --> 00:11.868
I'd say I'm sorry I asked,

00:11.870 --> 00:14.137
except I didn't.

00:14.139 --> 00:16.572
Oh, look, it's the
<i>Scientific American</i>

00:16.574 --> 00:19.384
that covered the paper
Leonard and I wrote.

00:19.386 --> 00:21.354
Oh, let me see.

00:21.356 --> 00:23.989
I have mixed feelings
about doing interviews.

00:23.991 --> 00:26.159
I like the part where I talk.

00:26.161 --> 00:29.833
I do not like the part
where the other man talks.

00:31.236 --> 00:34.107
Sheldon, this article doesn't
mention Leonard at all.

00:34.109 --> 00:35.876
Well, that
can't be right.

00:35.878 --> 00:38.948
It only refers to
“Dr. Cooper and his team.”

00:38.950 --> 00:40.845
Did you even talk about him?

00:40.847 --> 00:43.420
All I did was answer a few
questions about the theory.

00:43.422 --> 00:45.588
And then expressed my gratitude
that <i> Scientific American</i>

00:45.590 --> 00:49.052
doesn't include any of those
smelly perfume cards.

00:49.054 --> 00:51.691
Poor Leonard.

00:51.693 --> 00:54.026
Why? The theory
he came up with

00:54.028 --> 00:55.690
just got mentioned in
<i>Scientific American.</i>

00:55.692 --> 00:57.058
He ought to be thrilled.

00:57.060 --> 00:58.499
He might not be.

00:58.501 --> 01:00.530
Oh, maybe you're right.

01:00.532 --> 01:02.865
He is kind of a lump.

01:02.867 --> 01:04.000
Think about it.

01:04.001 --> 01:05.937
How would you feel
if you were referred to

01:05.939 --> 01:07.642
as part of Leonard's team?

01:07.644 --> 01:09.908
Oh, I'd be incensed.

01:09.910 --> 01:12.413
So you see what
I'm getting at?

01:12.415 --> 01:14.984
Squeaky wheel
gets the grease?

01:14.986 --> 01:16.386
No.

01:16.388 --> 01:18.290
Grass is always greener?

01:18.292 --> 01:19.995
Try again.

01:19.997 --> 01:21.659
Well, I don't know--
we're all Groot?

01:21.661 --> 01:23.764
Just tell me.

01:23.766 --> 01:25.836
Leonard is as much
a part of this paper

01:25.838 --> 01:27.900
as you are,
and he was overlooked.

01:27.902 --> 01:29.869
He's going to feel bad.

01:29.871 --> 01:32.141
But it wasn't my fault.

01:32.143 --> 01:33.676
I didn't exclude him.

01:33.678 --> 01:35.276
And I didn't write the article.

01:35.278 --> 01:38.348
Remember that time you didn't
get picked to pull the sword out

01:38.350 --> 01:41.579
of the stone at Disneyland and
they let that other kid do it?

01:41.581 --> 01:43.788
Oh, that kid!

01:46.592 --> 01:50.033
Poor Leonard.

01:50.035 --> 01:51.833
Exactly.

01:51.835 --> 01:54.265
For the record,
that kid was a terrible choice.

01:54.267 --> 01:56.034
If you cry when you drop
your churro,

01:56.036 --> 01:58.611
you do not have what it takes
to rule England.

01:59.814 --> 02:03.450
♪ Our whole universe
was in a hot, dense state ♪

02:03.452 --> 02:06.789
♪ Then nearly 14 billion years
ago expansion started... Wait! ♪

02:06.791 --> 02:08.429
♪ The Earth began to cool ♪

02:08.431 --> 02:10.967
♪ The autotrophs began to drool,
Neanderthals developed tools ♪

02:10.969 --> 02:13.642
♪ We built the Wall ♪
♪<i> We built the pyramids</i> ♪

02:13.644 --> 02:16.313
♪ Math, Science, History,
unraveling the mystery ♪

02:16.315 --> 02:18.153
♪ That all started
with a big bang ♪

02:18.154 --> 02:22.154
